description.text: After having some minor problems getting circles right and trying to get 608 bearings into my printed parts, I created this simple test to verify I had round holes. An American nickel is 21.21mm in diameter, and 1.95mm in thickness. Ref(http://www.usmint.gov/faqs/circulating_coins/?action=faq_circulating_coin) This test has an internal diameter of 22.0mm (what's 0.69mm between friends?) and a height of 1.95mm. This test will also be a good and quick test of the "Bottom" setting, and a good way to ensure the "Fill" settings are making solid top layers.

Print and place nickel in the middle. Make adjustments to your printer if needed, print again. As there are far too many calibration issues that you may run into for me to cover here, I'll direct you to the calibration page on the reprap wiki- (http://www.reprap.org/wiki/Calibration) It basically comes down to changing the steps per mm in the firmware.

description.text: "Sometimes I dream about finding a shiny new suit of powered armor out in the Wasteland. I'd have my pick of parts, I'd build the perfect suit just for me. Fresh off the line of a factory nobody's seen in a hundred years. But I know it will never happen. In the Wasteland, you're lucky to settle for 'gently used.' You'll find an arm here, a leg there. (And they're no fun to empty out!) Then you have to improvise. You may need to mix and match." Fallout Joe 2 includes two flavors of the West Tek T-45d Power Armor: Brotherhood of Steel or NCR Salvage. You can download a complete build plate (or both), or pick and choose individual parts to design a custom armor. You can also use parts from Fallout Joe with Fallout Joe 2. See the "Remix" section for links to accessories, stands, and the original Fallout Joe. In the future I hope to add alternate parts from Fallout Mods such as "Tribal Power Armor" with brahmin-skull shoulder pads, and the "Scorched Sierra Mk III" with bear furs. If anybody can help me get the Scorched Sierra models converted to OBJ or another Blender-compatible mesh it would be most appreciated! Edit 2015/11/24: Over the last couple of days I patched some rough spots on the Brotherhood of Steel breastplate piece. If the back of yours came out poorly, try the new version. This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/aVE2PE0SOmm and https://www.tinkercad.com/things/0VVYtUNtlLP

Notes: Set infill and resolution as you like. I've tried a range, it's fine anywhere. I've had the best luck building ball joints on 0.2 and 0.3, with break-away support enabled (Makerware 3.8). The joints seem to work better at a high resolution but sanding them helps considerably at lower resolution. Although PETG gives you the easiest joints – they'll flex better than ABS and need less finishing – my best results, by far, have been with HIPS-supported ABS. Much better detail. Much rounder ball joints. Default Makerware settings won't do, but with "extra support" up to 0.5 and z margins of 0.1 you get a great surface all around. You can get away with less support but the default doesn't seem to be enough.

When I decided to revisit Fallout Joe and do the more-common T-45d Power Armor, the most important thing to me was to make the parts compatible with my original Fallout Joe. I downloaded two T-45d models from the same source: tf3dm.com. One of them was in an odd format and I had to download a "Tomb Raider" modding tool to convert it to an OBJ file I could manipulate in Blender.
This time I used Blender to split the limbs apart. It gave me finer control over which parts I cut off than TinkerCAD. Beginning in Blender left less redundant, hidden geometry in the TinkerCAD file, so it takes less time to open and modify than FJ1. Even so, you can click 'Copy and Tinker' and go get yourself a coffee. Some brush-up was done in TinkerCAD, you can see that in gold. Joints still in red. I borrowed them directly from my original project so the limbs should line up properly when they're combined.

title: Roller Bearing Spool Holder for Replicator 2

description.text:
This is an improved Replicator 2 spool holder.  The improvements include:  
1) Turns very easily. the stiffness of the filiment even unwinds the spool a little.  
2) No pinching to get the spool on and off, a slight tilt keeps the spool on.  
3) Spool aimed slightly towards the filiment tube for better unwinding  
4) Spool doesn't rub on machine, no matter if the large or small hole are outward.

1) Print the shaft using 0.1 mm resolution, and support.  The shaft is sloped and the high resolution is needed so that the bearings don't rub against a stair case surface.  
2) Print the spool holder using support and normal resolution.  The support is only needed for that little lip at the end.  It may not be necessary but I haven't tried printing without support.  
3) Print 9 Roller Bearings.  No support is necessary  
4) Sand the roller bearings if there are any tabs at the end.  They should roll nicely on a flat table.  
5) Sand the inside lip of the spool holder to smooth it out a little.  
6) Hold the rollers and shaft in your hand as shown in the photo  
7) Slide the spool holder over the rollers and shaft.  
8) Attach to the Replicator 2, just like the stock spool holder.  
This design will have to be mirrored if you want to use it on the other side.

title: Star Wars themed light up Pencil Holder

description.text: Here is a pencil holder that is star wars themed. It has the star wars logo on one side, the Jedi logo, the sith logo, and the rebels logo. There are little holes on the lower rim of each face which can house 2 LEDs per face. There is also an electronics housing which attaches to the bottom of the pencil holder. The led holes lead to the little slots on the electronics housing so that you can run wires and the electronics housing can hold your wires and resistors and batteries. Comment down below if u have any questions or concerns.

Assembly You can print the whole thing at once pre assembled, it should be one of the stl files attached. This wont let you put in LED's but u dont have to assemble it. You can print the 4 faces pre attached and have the base plate and electronics board separately so that you can remove them to wire LEDs, or you can print each part and assemble the whole thing. To assemble attach all 4 faces together first. Then create your LED circuit. I will post a schematic or picture of my circuit soon so you can see if you dont know how to do that yourself. I suggest wiring the LED's in parallel and have a resistor in series. Also put the LED's with connecting wires down the holes in the faces first, then wire up the batteries and resistors. Finally attach the electronics housing on the bottom by inserting the pegs in the holes. And then take the base plate and put it in from the top of the pencil holder (dont glue the base plate down. Comment if u have questions and i will post a video soon on how to do it so that it is more clearer.

description.text:
This is a safety latch designed to secure drawers, cupboard doors, or other furniture to prevent young children from opening them. Commercially there is a wide variety in the design of these latches, however, I've kept this design to it's simplest and most utilitarian form. This should be printable on most reprap printers. If your printer can't handle the screw holes at the base of the latch then you could fill them solid and screw through the plastic when attaching the latch. This is a work in progress so I welcome your feedback, improvement, and derivative designs. This thing was made with Tinkercad.
Edit Part A online at: https://tinkercad.com/p/acc0011db8cb8e88
Edit Part B online at: https://tinkercad.com/p/acc0e35af491e43d

• Print both parts
  • Use two small wood screws to attach part b to the door/drawer. Take care to align it so the end of the latch has less than 1mm of clearance with the surface of the furniture when the door/drawer is closed.
  • Use two small wood screws to attach part a to the furniture surface.
  • When the door/drawer closes the latch should clip shut as part b is secured by part a.
  • Now to open the door/drawer you will have to flex the latch, young children struggle to do this so you have prevented them from getting access. Use Caution: Safety latches such as this design are not foolproof, and older children will learn how to open them. So it is important to keep dangerous substances out of reach or locked away.

description.text: Couples a 5mm motor shaft to an 8mm threaded rod, ensuring they are coaxial, but allowing some angular movement if the rod is not straight. This version has the advantage of using two identical parts, rather than having a captive-nut side, and a smooth side. This means that one needs one fewer part type, which seems like a good idea, but it also ensures that the bolts balance one another. As mentioned here: http://things.hands.com/thing/pla_coupling/ this version avoids the use of center=true, which seems to have been causing printing difficulties for some reason (as yet undetermined). Oh, and it has round corners (it's mostly an intersection of a 'cube' and a cylinder)

Place some plastic tubing over the motor shaft and then clamp it with M3x20 bolts
Alternatively (as mentioned in the comment by Pointedstick) one can reduce the diameter of the smaller radius hole to 2.5mm, and forget about the tubing, but this will of course reduce the suspension element of the design, so will presumably be less tolerant of bent rods.

I have included photos of the quick test print I did of the model in ABS. They are a bit rough, but that is more the manner of the print than the model itself. Notes: This is a simple straight froward print. The critical aspect is your bed adhesion and removal technique. The visible face of the cover needs to be printed face down so plan your materials and removal technique accordingly. You don't want to give yourself extra post processing work if you mar it during the bed removal. My test print was just a quick print in ABS and I had some marks on the face due to a rough removal. Nothing serious. In the future we plan to add designs and logos to the face side which will make the print more difficult. Our tentative plan is to print cover face up with support on the inside to minimize post processing on the cover face.

This is a printable conversion of an open released file from Intel for the INTEL NUC case cover. I have added the original released file from Intel, but it can also be found here:http://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/nuc/nuc-replaceable-lid.html I converted the file by loading it into Autodesk Fusion 360. I then exported it as a STL file. I used Netfab Basic to clean up the STL file. I then reexported it as a new STL file. This process was new to me so I need to thank r\3dprinting group over on Reddit and user ubermeisters for thier help.

title: Improved Quadcopter Motormounts A and B

description.text: After a buddy of mine had a few accidents with indoor Quadcopter flights we ran out of all of our spare motor mounts, so we started printing them off of thingiverse. We found that the bolt holes on the parts weren't a perfect match for the originals so decided to design our own.  Included are both A and B parts along with the original .SLDPRT files in case you have access to Solidworks or a higher-end 3D printer.

We added screw and motor recesses on both sides which means you should print with care. If you are using a MakerBot or something without support material, I would recommend putting the motor recess face down as this is very easy to ream out by hand with a drill bit.  
Also note, we played around with the screw hole diameters until we had something that printed out ok.  If you have a very hi-resolution machine (like a ZDimension printer) they may be about 0.5mm oversized.

title: Modified 2.5" to 3.5" adapter tray for Microserver caddy

description.text: I modified Apexio's tray design as his one caused my drives to sit 2mm too high making the SATA connector slightly out of alignment with the slot.  I also made it a bit thicker to give it more rigidity, and I chopped some holes in the non-vital parts to make it print faster and use less plastic.  Used to mount 2.5" SSDs into our HP Microserver using the original HP non-hotplug 3.5" drive caddy/trays.

I printed mine at .2mm layers, 100% infill.  I suggest drilling out the holes to clean them up, and screwing the screws in slowly as they need to tap a thread, and they tend to split the side if you are too rough screwing them in.  If you are worried about the unsupported corner, you can always drill a hole in the HP plastic caddy and screw directly into the 2.5" drive (I didnt find it necessary).

Sierpinski's tetrahedra (fractal tetrahedra) calculated by OpenSCAD. 
(update Nov. 12, 2015)  Initial parameters were for my temporal work.  Now set to fractal level = 5, thickd = 0.5 (mm, depth of "point contact" part).

Printer:

Da Vinci 2.0 Duo

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Notes: This is very simple object, but be careful... VERY FRAGILE OBJECT!! The density is very low, and I could hardly print level 5 fractal object. When removing supports, I broke many parts, and glued (ABS) with acetone. :-) Application of acetone is also helpful to make the bone structure firmly. tetra[1-6].stl are 1.0mm normalized size, and generated as is. See comments in OpenSCAD source for size specs and rotation angle. These stl files may not be good for printing - I suggest each printers use OpenSCAD, adjust the thickd & thickr parameters and print. The thickd adds thickness (make bigger triangle) at the contact point; if too small, the object cannot be printed but if too big, smaller "eyes" will be blocked. The thickr adds proportional thickness, but I don't think it's useful; if certain amount, then "eyes" won't be ordered equally, not beautiful. You may think it's better to rotate to (1) "normal angle" - top corner, bottom surface tetrahedron (the program comment mentions that angle). However, each part has ceilings, which need supports. It's hard to remove the support without harming the "point contact" part of tetrahedra.
I also tried (2) bottom corner, with 3 outer supports (generated simultaneously in OpenSCAD), (3) bottom edge (as the tetra[1-6].stl data is), with supports (generated by MeshMixer). On my printer, (2) failed because the "point contact" parts cannot stand the reversed tetrahedra, (3) failed because of the supports firmly gets into the object (still trying). If certain supports could be generated, direction of (3) will be the best. The tetra-nosup.scad source is for generating (2), and the generated example (70.7mm edge, 0.5mm contact point) is at tetra5-70_7d0_5revsup_fixed.stl . Try printing without support, cut the support carefully.

Fractal cube known as Menger's Sponge (or 3D Sierpinski's carpet).
This shape has infinite area and zero volume - it means very hard to calculate (time/memory) in higher order, and hard to 3D print-out.
I could calculate up to 4th order using PC and 3rd order using cheap FDM printer. Expecting anybody challenge more!!

I used cube.scad for OpenSCAD.
This shape is famous because of explode of calculation/memory, so 3rd order was the limit. Another method is, generating fractal "corridor" (with cubedig.scad) copy & rotate into Z->X/Y axis direction, then subtract (boolean difference) from cube. However in this method, 4rth order was the limit. The "cubedig4-dig145.stl" is 145mm cube corridor (note: the corridor is a bit longer than 145mm). The result (resized into 1/3) is "cubedig4_48.33," generated by Blender. After these efforts, I found my 3D printer (Da Vinci) cannot print over 3rd order - density of the object is too low, and too fragile.

These are parts to mount a standard 214*214 MK3 Heatbed plus the glass plate onto the vertex z-axis. (For printing them place them flat with the M4 nutholes facing to the top) For this to assemble you'll need 9 M4 Nuts and 9 M4 Screws, you can use any length you want for the screws but you'll need to use washers (you can print washers, just a cilinder) so the screw won't hit the bed. There are also holes for screws are pins in the corner pieces to keep the heatbed on it's place, though this isn't necessary due to the desigh it should stay put pretty good.
Also I have put some extra M4 nut holes on the back corners cause maybe in the future I'll be making some extra's to mount on the bed. But for normal use these aren't necessary. The middle part is extendable so it would fit perfect on your vertex 3d printer.
Also it was easier to do it this way than keep reprinting and readjusting the file till it would fit. Cause my first print was a bit too small, though it was measured almost perfectly. If you only want to use the MK3 214*214 heatbed on this mounting mechanism then you'll have to print 4 of the HeatbedCorner files (or the MIR, mirrored ones, they are both the same actually).
And so you don't need the back corners, since these have an addition to the standard corners to keep the glassplate on the heatbed. It is recommended to use heat resistant material as ABS, but you can also ofcourse spray it with heat resistant paint as I did. (I used the Motip Black Heat Resistant paint) Also after the assembly make sure you readjust the z axis calibration (rotate it to the left) just to be safe so the print head won't crash into the bed assembly.
What you can do is mount these pieces then do auto home and you'll see if the bed gets too high or not, but don't mount the glassplate and the heatbed before you adjusted the z axis. Update 10/11/2015:
I adjusted the back corner pieces so the glass plate would slide in , instead of just laying it in the corner pieces. Update 11/11/2015:
The front corners are now also adjusted so they hold the glassplate a bit better.
Also I have made some sort of clamp to be screwd into the front corners to hold the glassplate down. (Lockingmech1 and 2 and their mirrored files) You need a small screw for that, 2-3mm in diameter. Update 20/11/2015:
Since I myself need some sort of isolation to keep the bed at a high temperature, I adjusted the mounting pieces and added 2mm of depth, so you can easily place some sort of isolation that is max 2mm thick under the heatbed.
The files for this you can find in the zipped file: HeatBedMountingV2Isolation.7z If you have any questions don't hesitate to ask!
